# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: operator-algebras
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] This ensures that the multiplication operation is continuous with respect to the metric topology.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] A Banach algebra is called *unital* if it has an identity element for the multiplication whose norm is $1,$ and *commutative* if its multiplication is commutative.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Any Banach algebra A (whether it is unital or not) can be embedded isometrically into a unital Banach algebra $A_{e}$ so as to form a closed ideal of $A_{e}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Often one assumes *a priori* that the algebra under consideration is unital because one can develop much of the theory by considering $A_{e}$ and then applying the outcome in the original algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] However, this is not the case all the time.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] For example, one cannot define all the trigonometric functions in a Banach algebra without identity.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] The theory of real Banach algebras can be very different from the theory of complex Banach algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] For example, the spectrum of an element of a nontrivial complex Banach algebra can never be empty, whereas in a real Banach algebra it could be empty for some elements.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Banach algebras can also be defined over fields of p -adic numbers.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] The prototypical example of a Banach algebra is $C_{0}(X)$ , the space of (complex-valued) continuous functions, defined on a locally compact Hausdorff space X , that vanish at infinity. $C_{0}(X)$ is unital if and only if X is compact.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] The complex conjugation being an involution, $C_{0}(X)$ is in fact a C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] More generally, every C*-algebra is a Banach algebra by definition.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Several elementary functions that are defined via power series may be defined in any unital Banach algebra; examples include the exponential function and the trigonometric functions, and more generally any entire function.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] (In particular, the exponential map can be used to define abstract index groups.) The formula for the geometric series remains valid in general unital Banach algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] The binomial theorem also holds for two commuting elements of a Banach algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] The set of invertible elements in any unital Banach algebra is an open set, and the inversion operation on this set is continuous (and hence is a homeomorphism), so that it forms a topological group under multiplication.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] The various algebras of functions given in the examples above have very different properties from standard examples of algebras such as the reals.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Unital Banach algebras over the complex field provide a general setting to develop spectral theory.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] When the Banach algebra A is the algebra $L(X)$ of bounded linear operators on a complex Banach space X (for example, the algebra of square matrices), the notion of the spectrum in A coincides with the usual one in operator theory.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] The norm of a normal element x of a C*-algebra coincides with its spectral radius.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] This generalizes an analogous fact for normal operators.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Let A be a complex unital Banach algebra in which every non-zero element x is invertible (a division algebra).
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] For every $a\in A,$ there is $\lambda \in \mathbb {C}$ such that $a-\lambda \mathbf {1}$ is not invertible (because the spectrum of a is not empty) hence $a=\lambda \mathbf {1} :$ this algebra A is naturally isomorphic to $\mathbb {C}$ (the complex case of the Gelfand–Mazur theorem).
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Moreover, the norm (that is, operator norm) of a character is one.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] Equipped with the topology of pointwise convergence on A (that is, the topology induced by the weak-* topology of $A^{*}$ ), the character space, $\Delta (A),$ is a compact Hausdorff space.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] As an algebra, a unital commutative Banach algebra is semisimple (that is, its Jacobson radical is zero) if and only if its Gelfand representation has trivial kernel.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] An important example of such an algebra is a commutative C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] In other words, a Banach *-algebra is a Banach algebra over $\mathbb {C}$ that is also a *-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/banach-algebra] In most natural examples, one also has that the involution is isometric, that is, $\|x^{*}\|=\|x\|\quad {\text{ for all }}x\in A.$ Some authors include this isometric property in the definition of a Banach *-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In mathematics, specifically in functional analysis, a **C∗-algebra** (pronounced "C-star") is a Banach algebra together with an involution satisfying the properties of the adjoint.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Another important class of non-Hilbert C*-algebras includes the algebra $C_{0}(X)$ of complex-valued continuous functions on *X* that vanish at infinity, where *X* is a locally compact Hausdorff space.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] C*-algebras were first considered primarily for their use in quantum mechanics to model algebras of physical observables.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This line of research began with Werner Heisenberg's matrix mechanics and in a more mathematically developed form with Pascual Jordan around 1933.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Subsequently, John von Neumann attempted to establish a general framework for these algebras, which culminated in a series of papers on rings of operators.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] These papers considered a special class of C*-algebras that are now known as von Neumann algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Around 1943, the work of Israel Gelfand and Mark Naimark yielded an abstract characterisation of C*-algebras making no reference to operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] C*-algebras are now an important tool in the theory of unitary representations of locally compact groups, and are also used in algebraic formulations of quantum mechanics.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Another active area of research is the program to obtain classification, or to determine the extent of which classification is possible, for separable simple nuclear C*-algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] We begin with the abstract characterization of C*-algebras given in the 1943 paper by Gelfand and Naimark.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] which is sometimes called the B*-identity.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] For history behind the names C*- and B*-algebras, see the history section below.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The C*-identity is a very strong requirement.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In the case of C*-algebras, any *-homomorphism *π* between C*-algebras is contractive, i.e. bounded with norm ≤ 1.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Furthermore, an injective *-homomorphism between C*-algebras is isometric.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] These are consequences of the C*-identity.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] A bijective *-homomorphism *π* is called a **C*-isomorphism**, in which case *A* and *B* are said to be **isomorphic**.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The term B*-algebra was introduced by C.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This condition automatically implies that the *-involution is isometric, that is, $\lVert x\rVert =\lVert x^{*}\rVert$ .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Hence, $\lVert xx^{*}\rVert =\lVert x\rVert \lVert x^{*}\rVert$ , and therefore, a B*-algebra is also a C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Conversely, the C*-condition implies the B*-condition.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This is nontrivial, and can be proved without using the condition $\lVert x\rVert =\lVert x^{*}\rVert$ .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] For these reasons, the term B*-algebra is rarely used in current terminology, and has been replaced by the term 'C*-algebra'.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The term C*-algebra was introduced by I.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Segal in 1947 to describe norm-closed subalgebras of *B*(*H*), namely, the space of bounded operators on some Hilbert space *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In his paper Segal defines a C*-algebra as a "uniformly closed, self-adjoint algebra of bounded operators on a Hilbert space".
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] C*-algebras have a large number of properties that are technically convenient.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Some of these properties can be established by using the continuous functional calculus or by reduction to commutative C*-algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In the latter case, we can use the fact that the structure of these is completely determined by the Gelfand isomorphism.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Self-adjoint elements are those of the form $x=x^{*}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The set of elements of a C*-algebra *A* of the form $x^{*}x$ forms a closed convex cone.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This cone is identical to the elements of the form $xx^{*}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The set of self-adjoint elements of a C*-algebra *A* naturally has the structure of a partially ordered vector space; the ordering is usually denoted $\geq$ .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In this ordering, a self-adjoint element $x\in A$ satisfies $x\geq 0$ if and only if the spectrum of x is non-negative, if and only if $x=s^{*}s$ for some $s\in A$ .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Two self-adjoint elements x and y of *A* satisfy $x\geq y$ if $x-y\geq 0$ .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This partially ordered subspace allows the definition of a positive linear functional on a C*-algebra, which in turn is used to define the states of a C*-algebra, which in turn can be used to construct the spectrum of a C*-algebra using the GNS construction.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Any C*-algebra *A* has an approximate identity.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Using approximate identities, one can show that the algebraic quotient of a C*-algebra by a closed proper two-sided ideal, with the natural norm, is a C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Similarly, a closed two-sided ideal of a C*-algebra is itself a C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The algebra M(*n*, **C**) of *n* × *n* matrices over **C** becomes a C*-algebra if we consider matrices as operators on the Euclidean space, **C***n*, and use the operator norm ‖·‖ on matrices.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The involution is given by the conjugate transpose.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] More generally, one can consider finite direct sums of matrix algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In fact, all C*-algebras that are finite dimensional as vector spaces are of this form, up to isomorphism.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Each C*-algebra, *Ae*, is isomorphic (in a noncanonical way) to the full matrix algebra M(dim(*e*), **C**).
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The finite family indexed on min *A* given by {dim(*e*)}*e* is called the *dimension vector* of *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This vector uniquely determines the isomorphism class of a finite-dimensional C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In the language of K-theory, this vector is the positive cone of the *K*0 group of *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] A **†-algebra** (or, more explicitly, a *†-closed algebra*) is the name occasionally used in physics for a finite-dimensional C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The dagger, †, is used in the name because physicists typically use the symbol to denote a Hermitian adjoint, and are often not worried about the subtleties associated with an infinite number of dimensions.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] (Mathematicians usually use the asterisk, *, to denote the Hermitian adjoint.) †-algebras feature prominently in quantum mechanics, and especially quantum information science.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] An immediate generalization of finite dimensional C*-algebras are the approximately finite dimensional C*-algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The prototypical example of a C*-algebra is the algebra *B(H)* of bounded (equivalently continuous) linear operators defined on a complex Hilbert space *H*; here *x** denotes the adjoint operator of the operator *x* : *H* → *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In fact, every C*-algebra, *A*, is *-isomorphic to a norm-closed adjoint closed subalgebra of *B*(*H*) for a suitable Hilbert space, *H*; this is the content of the Gelfand–Naimark theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Let *H* be a separable infinite-dimensional Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The algebra *K*(*H*) of compact operators on *H* is a norm closed subalgebra of *B*(*H*).
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] It is also closed under involution; hence it is a C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Though *K*(*H*) does not have an identity element, a sequential approximate identity for *K*(*H*) can be developed.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] To be specific, *H* is isomorphic to the space of square summable sequences *l*2; we may assume that *H* = *l*2.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] For each natural number *n* let *Hn* be the subspace of sequences of *l*2 which vanish for indices *k* ≥ *n* and let *en* be the orthogonal projection onto *Hn*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The sequence {*en*}*n* is an approximate identity for *K*(*H*).
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Let *X* be a locally compact Hausdorff space.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The space $C_{0}(X)$ of complex-valued continuous functions on *X* that *vanish at infinity* (defined in the article on local compactness) forms a commutative C*-algebra $C_{0}(X)$ under pointwise multiplication and addition.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The involution is pointwise conjugation. $C_{0}(X)$ has a multiplicative unit element if and only if X is compact.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] As does any C*-algebra, $C_{0}(X)$ has an approximate identity.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In the case of $C_{0}(X)$ this is immediate: consider the directed set of compact subsets of X , and for each compact K let $f_{K}$ be a function of compact support which is identically 1 on K .
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Such functions exist by the Tietze extension theorem, which applies to locally compact Hausdorff spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Any such sequence of functions $\{f_{K}\}$ is an approximate identity.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The Gelfand representation states that every commutative C*-algebra is *-isomorphic to the algebra $C_{0}(X)$ , where X is the space of characters equipped with the weak* topology.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Furthermore, if $C_{0}(X)$ is isomorphic to $C_{0}(Y)$ as C*-algebras, it follows that X and Y are homeomorphic.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This characterization is one of the motivations for the noncommutative topology and noncommutative geometry programs.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Given a Banach *-algebra *A* with an approximate identity, there is a unique (up to C*-isomorphism) C*-algebra **E**(*A*) and *-morphism π from *A* into **E**(*A*) that is universal, that is, every other continuous *-morphism π ' : *A* → *B* factors uniquely through π.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The algebra **E**(*A*) is called the **C*-enveloping algebra** of the Banach *-algebra *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Of particular importance is the C*-algebra of a locally compact group *G*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This is defined as the enveloping C*-algebra of the group algebra of *G*.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The C*-algebra of *G* provides context for general harmonic analysis of *G* in the case *G* is non-abelian.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In particular, the dual of a locally compact group is defined to be the primitive ideal space of the group C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Von Neumann algebras, known as W* algebras before the 1960s, are a special kind of C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] They are required to be closed in the weak operator topology, which is weaker than the norm topology.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The Sherman–Takeda theorem implies that any C*-algebra has a universal enveloping W*-algebra, such that any homomorphism to a W*-algebra factors through it.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] A C*-algebra *A* is of type I if and only if for all non-degenerate representations π of *A* the von Neumann algebra π(*A*)″ (that is, the bicommutant of π(*A*)) is a type I von Neumann algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In fact it is sufficient to consider only factor representations, i.e. representations π for which π(*A*)″ is a factor.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] A locally compact group is said to be of type I if and only if its group C*-algebra is type I.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] However, if a C*-algebra has non-type I representations, then by results of James Glimm it also has representations of type II and type III.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] Thus for C*-algebras and locally compact groups, it is only meaningful to speak of type I and non type I properties.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] In quantum mechanics, one typically describes a physical system with a C*-algebra *A* with unit element; the self-adjoint elements of *A* (elements *x* with *x** = *x*) are thought of as the *observables*, the measurable quantities, of the system.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] A *state* of the system is defined as a positive functional on *A* (a **C**-linear map φ : *A* → **C** with φ(*u*u*) ≥ 0 for all *u* ∈ *A*) such that φ(1) = 1.
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] The expected value of the observable *x*, if the system is in state φ, is then φ(*x*).
[src:operator-algebras/c-algebra] This C*-algebra approach is used in the Haag–Kastler axiomatization of local quantum field theory, where every open set of Minkowski spacetime is associated with a C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In mathematics, the **Gelfand representation** in functional analysis (named after I.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In the former case, one may regard the Gelfand representation as a far-reaching generalization of the Fourier transform of an integrable function.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In the latter case, the Gelfand–Naimark representation theorem is one avenue in the development of spectral theory for normal operators, and generalizes the notion of diagonalizing a normal matrix.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] The importance of *X* being locally compact and Hausdorff is that this turns *X* into a completely regular space.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In such a space every closed subset of *X* is the common zero set of a family of continuous complex-valued functions on *X*, allowing one to recover the topology of *X* from *C*0(*X*).
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Note that *C*0(*X*) is unital if and only if *X* is compact, in which case *C*0(*X*) is equal to *C*(*X*), the algebra of all continuous complex-valued functions on *X*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Let A be a commutative Banach algebra, defined over the field $\mathbb {C}$ of complex numbers.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] A non-zero algebra homomorphism (a multiplicative linear functional) $\Phi \colon A\to \mathbb {C}$ is called a *character* of A ; the set of all characters of A is denoted by $\Phi _{A}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] It can be shown that every character on A is automatically continuous, and hence $\Phi _{A}$ is a subset of the space $A^{*}$ of continuous linear functionals on A ; moreover, when equipped with the relative weak-* topology, $\Phi _{A}$ turns out to be locally compact and Hausdorff.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] (This follows from the Banach–Alaoglu theorem.) The space $\Phi _{A}$ is compact (in the topology just defined) if and only if the algebra A has an identity element.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] The definition of $\Phi _{A}$ and the topology on it ensure that ${\widehat {a}}$ is continuous and vanishes at infinity, and that the map $a\mapsto {\widehat {a}}$ defines a norm-decreasing, unit-preserving algebra homomorphism from A to $C_{0}(\Phi _{A})$ .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] This homomorphism is the *Gelfand representation of A*, and ${\widehat {a}}$ is the *Gelfand transform* of the element a .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In general, the representation is neither injective nor surjective.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In the case where A has an identity element, there is a bijection between $\Phi _{A}$ and the set of maximal ideals in A (this relies on the Gelfand–Mazur theorem).
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] As a consequence, the kernel of the Gelfand representation $A\to C_{0}(\Phi _{A})$ may be identified with the Jacobson radical of A .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Thus the Gelfand representation is injective if and only if A is (Jacobson) semisimple.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] The Banach space $A=L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is a Banach algebra under the convolution, the group algebra of $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Then $\Phi _{A}$ is homeomorphic to $\mathbb {R}$ and the Gelfand transform of $f\in L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is the Fourier transform ${\tilde {f}}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Similarly, with $A=L^{1}(\mathbb {R} _{+})$ , the group algebra of the multiplicative reals, the Gelfand transform is the Mellin transform.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] For $A=\ell ^{\infty }$ , the representation space is the Stone–Čech compactification $\beta \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] More generally, if X is a completely regular Hausdorff space, then the representation space of the Banach algebra of bounded continuous functions is the Stone–Čech compactification of X .
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] As motivation, consider the special case *A* = *C*0(*X*).
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Then $\varphi _{x}$ is a character on *A*, and it can be shown that all characters of *A* are of this form; a more precise analysis shows that we may identify Φ*A* with *X*, not just as sets but as topological spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] The **spectrum** or **Gelfand space** of a commutative C*-algebra *A*, denoted *Â*, consists of the set of *non-zero* *-homomorphisms from *A* to the complex numbers.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Elements of the spectrum are called **characters** on *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In particular, the spectrum of a commutative C*-algebra is a locally compact Hausdorff space: In the unital case, i.e. where the C*-algebra has a multiplicative unit element 1, all characters *f* must be unital, i.e.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] So *Â* is closed under weak-* convergence and the spectrum is actually *compact*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In the non-unital case, the weak-* closure of *Â* is *Â* ∪ {0}, where 0 is the zero homomorphism, and the removal of a single point from a compact Hausdorff space yields a locally compact Hausdorff space.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Note that *spectrum* is an overloaded word.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] It also refers to the spectrum σ(*x*) of an element *x* of an algebra with unit 1, that is the set of complex numbers *r* for which *x* − *r* 1 is not invertible in *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] For unital C*-algebras, the two notions are connected in the following way: σ(*x*) is the set of complex numbers *f*(*x*) where *f* ranges over Gelfand space of *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Together with the spectral radius formula, this shows that *Â* is a subset of the unit ball of *A** and as such can be given the relative weak-* topology.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] This is the topology of pointwise convergence.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] A net {*f**k*}*k* of elements of the spectrum of *A* converges to *f* if and only if for each *x* in *A*, the net of complex numbers {*f**k*(*x*)}*k* converges to *f*(*x*).
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] If *A* is a separable C*-algebra, the weak-* topology is metrizable on bounded subsets.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Thus the spectrum of a separable commutative C*-algebra *A* can be regarded as a metric space.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] So the topology can be characterized via convergence of sequences.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Equivalently, σ(*x*) is the range of γ(*x*), where γ is the Gelfand representation.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] Let *A* be a commutative C*-algebra and let *X* be the spectrum of *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] be the Gelfand representation defined above.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] The spectrum of a commutative C*-algebra can also be viewed as the set of all maximal ideals *m* of *A*, with the hull-kernel topology.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] (See the earlier remarks for the general, commutative Banach algebra case.) For any such *m* the quotient algebra *A/m* is one-dimensional (by the Gelfand-Mazur theorem), and therefore any *a* in *A* gives rise to a complex-valued function on *Y*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In the case of C*-algebras with unit, the spectrum map gives rise to a contravariant functor from the category of commutative C*-algebras with unit and unit-preserving continuous *-homomorphisms, to the category of compact Hausdorff spaces and continuous maps.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] This functor is one half of a contravariant equivalence between these two categories (its adjoint being the functor that assigns to each compact Hausdorff space *X* the C*-algebra *C*0(*X*)).
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] In particular, given compact Hausdorff spaces *X* and *Y*, then *C*(*X*) is isomorphic to *C*(*Y*) (as a C*-algebra) if and only if *X* is homeomorphic to *Y*.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] The 'full' Gelfand–Naimark theorem is a result for arbitrary (abstract) noncommutative C*-algebras *A*, which though not quite analogous to the Gelfand representation, does provide a concrete representation of *A* as an algebra of operators.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] One of the most significant applications is the existence of a continuous functional calculus for normal elements in C*-algebra *A*: An element *x* is normal if and only if *x* commutes with its adjoint *x**, or equivalently if and only if it generates a commutative C*-algebra C*(*x*).
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] By the Gelfand isomorphism applied to C*(*x*) this is *-isomorphic to an algebra of continuous functions on a locally compact space.
[src:operator-algebras/gelfand-representation] This allows us to apply continuous functions to bounded normal operators on Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The mathematical concept of a **Hilbert space** generalizes the notion of Euclidean space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] It extends the methods of Euclidean geometry and calculus from the two-dimensional Euclidean plane and three-dimensional space to spaces of any finite or infinite dimension.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A Hilbert space is an abstract vector space, and it has the additional structure of an inner product that allows length and angle to be measured.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Finally, Hilbert spaces are required to be complete, a property that stipulates the existence of enough limits in the space to allow the techniques of calculus to be used.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces were studied beginning in the first decade of the 20th century by David Hilbert (after whom they are named), Erhard Schmidt, and Frigyes Riesz.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] They are indispensable tools in the theories of partial differential equations, quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis (which includes applications to signal processing and heat transfer), and ergodic theory (which forms the mathematical underpinning of thermodynamics).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] John von Neumann coined the term *Hilbert space* for the abstract concept that underlies many of these diverse applications.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The success of Hilbert space methods ushered in a very fruitful era for functional analysis.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Apart from the classical Euclidean vector spaces, examples of Hilbert spaces include spaces of square-integrable functions, spaces of sequences, Sobolev spaces consisting of generalized functions, and Hardy spaces of holomorphic functions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Geometric intuition plays an important role in many aspects of Hilbert space theory.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Exact analogs of the Pythagorean theorem and parallelogram law hold in a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] At a deeper level, perpendicular projection onto a linear subspace plays a significant role in optimization problems and other aspects of the theory.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] An element of a Hilbert space can be uniquely specified by its coordinates with respect to an orthonormal basis, in analogy with Cartesian coordinates in classical geometry.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] When this basis is countably infinite, it allows identifying the Hilbert space with the space of the infinite sequences that are square-summable.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The latter space is often in the older literature referred to as *the* Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] One of the most familiar examples of a Hilbert space is the Euclidean vector space consisting of three-dimensional vectors, denoted by $\mathbf {R} ^{3}$ , and equipped with the dot product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The dot product takes two vectors **x** and **y**, and produces a real number **x** ⋅ **y**.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] It is positive definite: for all vectors **x**, **x** ⋅ **x** ≥ 0 , with equality if and only if **x** = **0**.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] An operation on pairs of vectors that, like the dot product, satisfies these three properties is known as a (real) inner product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A vector space equipped with such an inner product is known as a (real) inner product space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Every finite-dimensional inner product space is also a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Multivariable calculus in Euclidean space relies on the ability to compute limits, and to have useful criteria for concluding that limits exist.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces are often taken over the complex numbers.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The real part of ⟨*z*, *w*⟩ gives the usual two-dimensional Euclidean dot product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A second example is the space **C**2 whose elements are pairs of complex numbers *z* = (*z*1, *z*2).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The real part of ⟨*z*, *w*⟩ is then the four-dimensional Euclidean dot product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A *Hilbert space* is a real or complex inner product space that is also a complete metric space with respect to the distance function induced by the inner product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The inner product is linear in its first argument.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A *real inner product space* is defined in the same way, except that *H* is a real vector space and the inner product takes real values.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Such an inner product will be a bilinear map and $(H,H,\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle )$ will form a dual system.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] This last property is ultimately a consequence of the more fundamental Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, which asserts $\left|\langle x,y\rangle \right|\leq \|x\|\|y\|$ with equality if and only if x and y are linearly dependent.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] With a distance function defined in this way, any inner product space is a metric space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] An inner product space is sometimes known as a *pre-Hilbert space*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Any pre-Hilbert space that is additionally also a complete space is a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The *completeness* of *H* is expressed using a form of the Cauchy criterion for sequences in *H*: a pre-Hilbert space *H* is complete if every Cauchy sequence converges with respect to this norm to an element in the space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] As a complete normed space, Hilbert spaces are by definition also Banach spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] As such they are topological vector spaces, in which topological notions like the openness and closedness of subsets are well defined.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Of special importance is the notion of a closed linear subspace of a Hilbert space that, with the inner product induced by restriction, is also complete (being a closed set in a complete metric space) and therefore a Hilbert space in its own right.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The sequence space ${\textstyle \ell ^{2}}$ consists of all infinite sequences **z** = (*z*1, *z*2, ...) of complex numbers such that the series $\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }|z_{n}|^{2}$ of its squared norms converges.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Completeness of the space holds provided that whenever a series of elements from ${\textstyle \ell ^{2}}$ converges absolutely (in norm), then it converges to an element of ${\textstyle \ell ^{2}}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The proof is basic in mathematical analysis, and permits mathematical series of elements of the space to be manipulated with the same ease as series of complex numbers (or vectors in a finite-dimensional Euclidean space).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Prior to the development of Hilbert spaces, other generalizations of Euclidean spaces were known to mathematicians and physicists.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Other objects studied at the turn of the 20th century, in particular spaces of sequences (including series) and spaces of functions, can naturally be thought of as linear spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Functions, for instance, can be added together or multiplied by constant scalars, and these operations obey the algebraic laws satisfied by addition and scalar multiplication of spatial vectors.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In the first decade of the 20th century, parallel developments led to the introduction of Hilbert spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] that has many of the familiar properties of the Euclidean dot product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, the idea of an orthogonal family of functions has meaning.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] where K is a continuous function symmetric in x and y.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] where the functions φn are orthogonal in the sense that ⟨*φ**n*, *φ**m*⟩ = 0 for all *n* ≠ *m*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The individual terms in this series are sometimes referred to as elementary product solutions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] However, there are eigenfunction expansions that fail to converge in a suitable sense to a square-integrable function: the missing ingredient, which ensures convergence, is completeness.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The second development was the Lebesgue integral, an alternative to the Riemann integral introduced by Henri Lebesgue in 1904.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Lebesgue integral made it possible to integrate a much broader class of functions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In 1907, Frigyes Riesz and Ernst Sigismund Fischer independently proved that the space *L*2 of square Lebesgue-integrable functions is a complete metric space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Further basic results were proved in the early 20th century.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For example, the Riesz representation theorem was independently established by Maurice Fréchet and Frigyes Riesz in 1907.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] John von Neumann coined the term *abstract Hilbert space* in his work on unbounded Hermitian operators.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Although other mathematicians such as Hermann Weyl and Norbert Wiener had already studied particular Hilbert spaces in great detail, often from a physically motivated point of view, von Neumann gave the first complete and axiomatic treatment of them.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Von Neumann later used them in his seminal work on the foundations of quantum mechanics, and in his continued work with Eugene Wigner.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The name "Hilbert space" was soon adopted by others, for example by Hermann Weyl in his book on quantum mechanics and the theory of groups.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The significance of the concept of a Hilbert space was underlined with the realization that it offers one of the best mathematical formulations of quantum mechanics.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In short, the states of a quantum mechanical system are vectors in a certain Hilbert space, the observables are hermitian operators on that space, the symmetries of the system are unitary operators, and measurements are orthogonal projections.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The relation between quantum mechanical symmetries and unitary operators provided an impetus for the development of the unitary representation theory of groups, initiated in the 1928 work of Hermann Weyl.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The algebra of observables in quantum mechanics is naturally an algebra of operators defined on a Hilbert space, according to Werner Heisenberg's matrix mechanics formulation of quantum theory.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Von Neumann began investigating operator algebras in the 1930s, as rings of operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Such algebras are now known as von Neumann algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators in particular that underlies much of the existing Hilbert space theory was generalized to C*-algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] These techniques are now basic in abstract harmonic analysis and representation theory.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Lebesgue spaces are function spaces associated to measure spaces (*X*, *M*, *μ*), where *X* is a set, *M* is a σ-algebra of subsets of *X*, and *μ* is a countably additive measure on *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] where the second form (conjugation of the first element) is commonly found in the theoretical physics literature.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For *f* and *g* in *L*2, the integral exists because of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, and defines an inner product on the space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Equipped with this inner product, *L*2 is in fact complete.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Lebesgue integral is essential to ensure completeness: on domains of real numbers, for instance, not enough functions are Riemann integrable.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Lebesgue spaces appear in many natural settings.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The spaces *L*2(**R**) and *L*2([0,1]) of square-integrable functions with respect to the Lebesgue measure on the real line and unit interval, respectively, are natural domains on which to define the Fourier transform and Fourier series.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In other situations, the measure may be something other than the ordinary Lebesgue measure on the real line.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For instance, if *w* is any positive measurable function, the space of all measurable functions *f* on the interval [0, 1] satisfying $\int _{0}^{1}{\bigl |}f(t){\bigr |}^{2}w(t)\,\mathrm {d} t<\infty$ is called the weighted *L*2 space *L*2 *w*([0, 1]), and *w* is called the weight function.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Weighted *L*2 spaces like this are frequently used to study orthogonal polynomials, because different families of orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal with respect to different weighting functions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Sobolev spaces, denoted by *H**s* or *W**s*,2, are Hilbert spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] These are a special kind of function space in which differentiation may be performed, but that (unlike other Banach spaces such as the Hölder spaces) support the structure of an inner product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Because differentiation is permitted, Sobolev spaces are a convenient setting for the theory of partial differential equations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] They also form the basis of the theory of direct methods in the calculus of variations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For *s* a non-negative integer and Ω ⊂ **R***n*, the Sobolev space *H**s*(Ω) contains *L*2 functions whose weak derivatives of order up to *s* are also *L*2.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Sobolev spaces can also be defined when *s* is not an integer.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Sobolev spaces are also studied from the point of view of spectral theory, relying more specifically on the Hilbert space structure.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Here Δ is the Laplacian and (1 − Δ)−*s* / 2 is understood in terms of the spectral mapping theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Apart from providing a workable definition of Sobolev spaces for non-integer *s*, this definition also has particularly desirable properties under the Fourier transform that make it ideal for the study of pseudodifferential operators.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Using these methods on a compact Riemannian manifold, one can obtain for instance the Hodge decomposition, which is the basis of Hodge theory.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Hardy spaces are function spaces, arising in complex analysis and harmonic analysis, whose elements are certain holomorphic functions in a complex domain.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Let *U* denote the unit disc in the complex plane.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Then the Hardy space *H*2(*U*) is defined as the space of holomorphic functions *f* on *U* such that the means $M_{r}(f)={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{0}^{2\pi }\left|f{\bigl (}re^{i\theta }{\bigr )}\right|^{2}\,\mathrm {d} \theta$ remain bounded for *r* < 1.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Hardy spaces in the disc are related to Fourier series.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Thus *H*2(*U*) consists of those functions that are *L*2 on the circle, and whose negative frequency Fourier coefficients vanish.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Bergman spaces are another family of Hilbert spaces of holomorphic functions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Clearly *L*2, *h*(*D*) is a subspace of *L*2(*D*); in fact, it is a closed subspace, and so a Hilbert space in its own right.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] This is a consequence of the estimate, valid on compact subsets *K* of *D*, that $\sup _{z\in K}\left|f(z)\right|\leq C_{K}\left\|f\right\|_{2}\,,$ which in turn follows from Cauchy's integral formula.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Thus convergence of a sequence of holomorphic functions in *L*2(*D*) implies also compact convergence, and so the limit function is also holomorphic.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Another consequence of this inequality is that the linear functional that evaluates a function *f* at a point of *D* is actually continuous on *L*2,*h*(*D*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Riesz representation theorem implies that the evaluation functional can be represented as an element of *L*2,*h*(*D*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The integrand $K(\zeta ,z)={\overline {\eta _{z}(\zeta )}}$ is known as the Bergman kernel of *D*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A Bergman space is an example of a reproducing kernel Hilbert space, which is a Hilbert space of functions along with a kernel *K*(*ζ*, *z*) that verifies a reproducing property analogous to this one.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Hardy space *H*2(*D*) also admits a reproducing kernel, known as the Szegő kernel.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Reproducing kernels are common in other areas of mathematics as well.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For instance, in harmonic analysis the Poisson kernel is a reproducing kernel for the Hilbert space of square-integrable harmonic functions in the unit ball.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The latter is a Hilbert space because the mean theorem for harmonic functions implies $L^{2}$ -bounded point evaluations, from which it follows that it is a closed subspace of $L^{2}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Many of the applications of Hilbert spaces exploit the fact that Hilbert spaces support generalizations of simple geometric concepts like projection and change of basis from their usual finite dimensional setting.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, the spectral theory of continuous self-adjoint linear operators on a Hilbert space generalizes the usual spectral decomposition of a matrix, and this often plays a major role in applications of the theory to other areas of mathematics and physics.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In the theory of ordinary differential equations, spectral methods on a suitable Hilbert space are used to study the behavior of eigenvalues and eigenfunctions of differential equations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For example, the Sturm–Liouville problem arises in the study of the harmonics of waves in a violin string or a drum, and is a central problem in ordinary differential equations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The problem only has solutions for certain values of *λ*, called eigenvalues of the system, and this is a consequence of the spectral theorem for compact operators applied to the integral operator defined by the Green's function for the system.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Furthermore, another consequence of this general result is that the eigenvalues *λ* of the system can be arranged in an increasing sequence tending to infinity.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces form a basic tool in the study of partial differential equations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For many classes of partial differential equations, such as linear elliptic equations, it is possible to consider a generalized solution (known as a weak solution) by enlarging the class of functions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Many weak formulations involve the class of Sobolev functions, which is a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A suitable weak formulation reduces to a geometrical problem, the analytic problem of finding a solution or, often what is more important, showing that a solution exists and is unique for given boundary data.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For linear elliptic equations, one geometrical result that ensures unique solvability for a large class of problems is the Lax–Milgram theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] This strategy forms the rudiment of the Galerkin method (a finite element method) for numerical solution of partial differential equations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] An example is the Poisson equation −Δ*u* = *g* with Dirichlet boundary conditions in a bounded domain Ω in **R**2.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] This can be recast in terms of the Hilbert space *H*1 0(Ω) consisting of functions *u* such that *u*, along with its weak partial derivatives, are square integrable on Ω, and vanish on the boundary.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Since the Poisson equation is elliptic, it follows from Poincaré's inequality that the bilinear form *a* is coercive.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Lax–Milgram theorem then ensures the existence and uniqueness of solutions of this equation.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces allow for many elliptic partial differential equations to be formulated in a similar way, and the Lax–Milgram theorem is then a basic tool in their analysis.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] With suitable modifications, similar techniques can be applied to parabolic partial differential equations and certain hyperbolic partial differential equations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The field of ergodic theory is the study of the long-term behavior of chaotic dynamical systems.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The laws of thermodynamics are assertions about such average behavior.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, one formulation of the zeroth law of thermodynamics asserts that over sufficiently long timescales, the only functionally independent measurement that one can make of a thermodynamic system in equilibrium is its total energy, in the form of temperature.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] An ergodic dynamical system is one for which, apart from the energy—measured by the Hamiltonian—there are no other functionally independent conserved quantities on the phase space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] More explicitly, suppose that the energy *E* is fixed, and let Ω*E* be the subset of the phase space consisting of all states of energy *E* (an energy surface), and let *T**t* denote the evolution operator on the phase space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The dynamical system is ergodic if every invariant measurable function on Ω*E* is constant almost everywhere.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] An invariant function *f* is one for which $f(T_{t}w)=f(w)$ for all *w* on Ω*E* and all time *t*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Liouville's theorem implies that there exists a measure *μ* on the energy surface that is invariant under the time translation.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] That is, the long time average of an observable *f* is equal to its expectation value over an energy surface.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] One of the basic goals of Fourier analysis is to decompose a function into a (possibly infinite) linear combination of given basis functions: the associated Fourier series.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The example of adding up the first few terms in a Fourier series for a sawtooth function is shown in the figure.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The basis functions are sine waves with wavelengths ⁠*λ*/*n*⁠ (for integer *n*) shorter than the wavelength *λ* of the sawtooth itself (except for *n* = 1, the *fundamental* wave).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A significant problem in classical Fourier series asks in what sense the Fourier series converges, if at all, to the function *f*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert space methods provide one possible answer to this question.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The functions *en*(*θ*) = *e*2π*inθ* form an orthogonal basis of the Hilbert space *L*2([0, 1]).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Consequently, any square-integrable function can be expressed as a series $f(\theta )=\sum _{n}a_{n}e_{n}(\theta )\,,\quad a_{n}=\langle f,e_{n}\rangle$ and, moreover, this series converges in the Hilbert space sense (that is, in the *L*2 mean).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The problem can also be studied from the abstract point of view: every Hilbert space has an orthonormal basis, and every element of the Hilbert space can be written in a unique way as a sum of multiples of these basis elements.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The coefficients appearing on these basis elements are sometimes known abstractly as the Fourier coefficients of the element of the space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The abstraction is especially useful when it is more natural to use different basis functions for a space such as *L*2([0, 1]).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In many circumstances, it is desirable not to decompose a function into trigonometric functions, but rather into orthogonal polynomials or wavelets for instance, and in higher dimensions into spherical harmonics.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The coefficients {*a**j*} are selected to make the magnitude of the difference ‖*f* − *f**n*‖2 as small as possible.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] That this formula minimizes the difference ‖*f* − *f**n*‖2 is a consequence of Bessel's inequality and Parseval's formula.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In various applications to physical problems, a function can be decomposed into physically meaningful eigenfunctions of a differential operator (typically the Laplace operator): this forms the foundation for the spectral study of functions, in reference to the spectrum of the differential operator.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A concrete physical application involves the problem of hearing the shape of a drum: given the fundamental modes of vibration that a drumhead is capable of producing, can one infer the shape of the drum itself?
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The mathematical formulation of this question involves the Dirichlet eigenvalues of the Laplace equation in the plane, that represent the fundamental modes of vibration in direct analogy with the integers that represent the fundamental modes of vibration of the violin string.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Spectral theory also underlies certain aspects of the Fourier transform of a function.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Fourier transformation is also geometrical, in a sense made precise by the Plancherel theorem, that asserts that it is an isometry of one Hilbert space (the "time domain") with another (the "frequency domain").
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In other words, the possible states are points in the projectivization of a Hilbert space, usually called the complex projective space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Each observable is represented by a self-adjoint linear operator acting on the state space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Each eigenstate of an observable corresponds to an eigenvector of the operator, and the associated eigenvalue corresponds to the value of the observable in that eigenstate.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The inner product between two state vectors is a complex number known as a probability amplitude.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] During an ideal measurement of a quantum mechanical system, the probability that a system collapses from a given initial state to a particular eigenstate is given by the square of the absolute value of the probability amplitudes between the initial and final states.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The possible results of a measurement are the eigenvalues of the operator—which explains the choice of self-adjoint operators, for all the eigenvalues must be real.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The probability distribution of an observable in a given state can be found by computing the spectral decomposition of the corresponding operator.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] For a general system, states are typically not pure, but instead are represented as statistical mixtures of pure states, or mixed states, given by density matrices: self-adjoint operators of trace one on a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Moreover, for general quantum mechanical systems, the effects of a single measurement can influence other parts of a system in a manner that is described instead by a positive operator valued measure.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Thus the structure both of the states and observables in the general theory is considerably more complicated than the idealization for pure states.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In probability theory, Hilbert spaces also have diverse applications.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Here a fundamental Hilbert space is the space of random variables on a given probability space, having class $L^{2}$ (finite first and second moments).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A common operation in statistics is that of centering a random variable by subtracting its expectation.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Thus if X is a random variable, then $X-E(X)$ is its centering.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In the Hilbert space view, this is the orthogonal projection of X onto the kernel of the expectation operator, which a continuous linear functional on the Hilbert space (in fact, the inner product with the constant random variable 1), and so this kernel is a closed subspace.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The conditional expectation has a natural interpretation in the Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Suppose that a probability space $(\Omega ,P,{\mathcal {B}})$ is given, where ${\mathcal {B}}$ is a sigma algebra on the set $\Omega$ , and P is a probability measure on the measure space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {B}})$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] If ${\mathcal {F}}\leq {\mathcal {B}}$ is a sigma subalgebra of ${\mathcal {B}}$ , then the conditional expectation $E[X\mid {\mathcal {F}}]$ is the orthogonal projection of X onto the subspace of $L^{2}(\Omega ,P)$ consisting of the ${\mathcal {F}}$ -measurable functions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] If the random variable X in $L^{2}(\Omega ,P)$ is independent of the sigma algebra ${\mathcal {F}}$ then conditional expectation $E(X\mid {\mathcal {F}})=E(X)$ , i.e., its projection onto the ${\mathcal {F}}$ -measurable functions is constant.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Equivalently, the projection of its centering is zero.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, if two random variables X and Y (in $L^{2}(\Omega ,P)$ ) are independent, then the centered random variables $X-E(X)$ and $Y-E(Y)$ are orthogonal.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The analysis of variance could use the Pythagorean Theorem so that the variance is viewed as the decomposition of the squared length of a vector into the sum of the squared lengths of several vectors.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The theory of martingales can be formulated in Hilbert spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A martingale in a Hilbert space is a sequence $x_{1},x_{2},\dots$ of elements of a Hilbert space such that, for each *n*, $x_{n}$ is the orthogonal projection of $x_{n+1}$ onto the linear hull of $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] If the $x_{k}$ are random variables, this reproduces the usual definition of a (discrete) martingale: the expectation of $x_{n+1}$ , conditioned on $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ , is equal to $x_{n}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces are also used throughout the foundations of the Itô calculus.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] To any square-integrable martingale, it is possible to associate a Hilbert norm on the space of equivalence classes of progressively measurable processes with respect to the martingale (using the quadratic variation of the martingale as the measure).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The Itô integral can be constructed by first defining it for simple processes, and then exploiting their density in the Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] A deeper application of Hilbert spaces that is especially important in the theory of Gaussian processes is an attempt, due to Leonard Gross and others, to make sense of certain formal integrals over infinite dimensional spaces like the Feynman path integral from quantum field theory.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The problem with integrals like this is that there is no infinite dimensional Lebesgue measure.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The notion of an abstract Wiener space allows one to construct a measure on a Banach space *B* that contains a Hilbert space *H*, called the Cameron–Martin space, as a dense subset, out of a finitely additive cylinder set measure on *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The resulting measure on *B* is countably additive and invariant under translation by elements of *H*, and this provides a mathematically rigorous way of thinking of the Wiener measure as a Gaussian measure adapted to the Sobolev space $H^{1}([0,\infty ))$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Any true physical color can be represented by a combination of pure spectral colors.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] As physical colors can be composed of any number of spectral colors, the space of physical colors may aptly be represented by a Hilbert space over spectral colors.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] Humans have three types of cone cells for color perception, so the perceivable colors can be represented by 3-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p01] The many-to-one linear mapping from the Hilbert space of physical colors to the Euclidean space of human perceivable colors explains why many distinct physical colors may be perceived by humans to be identical (e.g., pure yellow light versus a mix of red and green light, see *Metamerism*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Two vectors *u* and *v* in a Hilbert space *H* are orthogonal when ⟨*u*, *v*⟩ = 0.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] More generally, when *S* is a subset in *H*, the notation *u* ⊥ *S* means that *u* is orthogonal to every element from *S*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Whereas the Pythagorean identity as stated is valid in any inner product space, completeness is required for the extension of the Pythagorean identity to series.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] By definition, every Hilbert space is also a Banach space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, every Banach space in which the parallelogram identity holds is a Hilbert space, and the inner product is uniquely determined by the norm by the polarization identity.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The parallelogram law implies that any Hilbert space is a uniformly convex Banach space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This subsection employs the Hilbert projection theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This is equivalent to saying that there is a point with minimal norm in the translated convex set *D* = *C* − *x*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The proof consists in showing that every minimizing sequence (*dn*) ⊂ *D* is Cauchy (using the parallelogram identity) hence converges (using completeness) to a point in *D* that has minimal norm.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] More generally, this holds in any uniformly convex Banach space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This point *y* is the *orthogonal projection* of *x* onto *F*, and the mapping *PF* : *x* → *y* is linear (see *§ Orthogonal complements and projections*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This result is especially significant in applied mathematics, especially numerical analysis, where it forms the basis of least squares methods.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In particular, when *F* is not equal to *H*, one can find a nonzero vector *v* orthogonal to *F* (select *x* ∉ *F* and *v* = *x* − *y*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] A very useful criterion is obtained by applying this observation to the closed subspace *F* generated by a subset *S* of *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The dual space *H** is the space of all continuous linear functions from the space *H* into the base field.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] It carries a natural norm, defined by $\|\varphi \|=\sup _{\|x\|=1,x\in H}|\varphi (x)|\,.$ This norm satisfies the parallelogram law, and so the dual space is also an inner product space where this inner product can be defined in terms of this dual norm by using the polarization identity.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The dual space is also complete so it is a Hilbert space in its own right.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *e*• = (*e**i*)*i* ∈ *I* is a complete orthonormal basis for H then the inner product on the dual space of any two $f,g\in H^{*}$ is $\langle f,g\rangle _{H^{*}}=\sum _{i\in I}f(e_{i}){\overline {g(e_{i})}}$ where all but countably many of the terms in this series are zero.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The Riesz representation theorem affords a convenient description of the dual space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The Riesz representation theorem states that the map from *H* to *H** defined by *u* ↦ *φu* is surjective, which makes this map an isometric antilinear isomorphism.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] So to every element *φ* of the dual *H** there exists one and only one *uφ* in *H* such that $\langle x,u_{\varphi }\rangle =\varphi (x)$ for all *x* ∈ *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The reversal of order on the right-hand side restores linearity in *φ* from the antilinearity of *uφ*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In the real case, the antilinear isomorphism from *H* to its dual is actually an isomorphism, and so real Hilbert spaces are naturally isomorphic to their own duals.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The representing vector *uφ* is obtained in the following way.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] When *φ* ≠ 0, the kernel *F* = Ker(*φ*) is a closed vector subspace of *H*, not equal to *H*, hence there exists a nonzero vector *v* orthogonal to *F*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The vector *u* is a suitable scalar multiple *λv* of *v*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This correspondence *φ* ↔ *u* is exploited by the bra–ket notation popular in physics.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] It is common in physics to assume that the inner product, denoted by ⟨*x*|*y*⟩, is linear on the right, $\langle x|y\rangle =\langle y,x\rangle \,.$ The result ⟨*x*|*y*⟩ can be seen as the action of the linear functional ⟨*x*| (the *bra*) on the vector |*y*⟩ (the *ket*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The Riesz representation theorem relies fundamentally not just on the presence of an inner product, but also on the completeness of the space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In fact, the theorem implies that the topological dual of any inner product space can be identified with its completion.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] An immediate consequence of the Riesz representation theorem is also that a Hilbert space *H* is reflexive, meaning that the natural map from *H* into its double dual space is an isomorphism.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In a Hilbert space *H*, a sequence {*xn*} is weakly convergent to a vector *x* ∈ *H* when $\lim _{n}\langle x_{n},v\rangle =\langle x,v\rangle$ for every *v* ∈ *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] For example, any orthonormal sequence {*fn*} converges weakly to 0, as a consequence of Bessel's inequality.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Every weakly convergent sequence {*xn*} is bounded, by the uniform boundedness principle.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, every bounded sequence in a Hilbert space admits weakly convergent subsequences (Alaoglu's theorem).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This fact may be used to prove minimization results for continuous convex functionals, in the same way that the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem is used for continuous functions on **R***d*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This fact (and its various generalizations) are fundamental for direct methods in the calculus of variations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Minimization results for convex functionals are also a direct consequence of the slightly more abstract fact that closed bounded convex subsets in a Hilbert space *H* are weakly compact, since *H* is reflexive.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The existence of weakly convergent subsequences is a special case of the Eberlein–Šmulian theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Any general property of Banach spaces continues to hold for Hilbert spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The open mapping theorem states that a continuous surjective linear transformation from one Banach space to another is an open mapping meaning that it sends open sets to open sets.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] A corollary is the bounded inverse theorem, that a continuous and bijective linear function from one Banach space to another is an isomorphism (that is, a continuous linear map whose inverse is also continuous).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This theorem is considerably simpler to prove in the case of Hilbert spaces than in general Banach spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The open mapping theorem is equivalent to the closed graph theorem, which asserts that a linear function from one Banach space to another is continuous if and only if its graph is a closed set.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In the case of Hilbert spaces, this is basic in the study of unbounded operators (see *Closed operator*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The (geometrical) Hahn–Banach theorem asserts that a closed convex set can be separated from any point outside it by means of a hyperplane of the Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This is an immediate consequence of the best approximation property: if *y* is the element of a closed convex set *F* closest to *x*, then the separating hyperplane is the plane perpendicular to the segment *xy* passing through its midpoint.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The continuous linear operators *A* : *H*1 → *H*2 from a Hilbert space *H*1 to a second Hilbert space *H*2 are *bounded* in the sense that they map bounded sets to bounded sets.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, if an operator is bounded, then it is continuous.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The sum and the composite of two bounded linear operators is again bounded and linear.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] For *y* in *H*2, the map that sends *x* ∈ *H*1 to ⟨*Ax*, *y*⟩ is linear and continuous, and according to the Riesz representation theorem can therefore be represented in the form $\left\langle x,A^{*}y\right\rangle =\langle Ax,y\rangle$ for some vector *A***y* in *H*1.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This defines another bounded linear operator *A** : *H*2 → *H*1, the adjoint of *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The set B(*H*) of all bounded linear operators on *H* (meaning operators *H* → *H*), together with the addition and composition operations, the norm and the adjoint operation, is a C*-algebra, which is a type of operator algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] An element *A* of B(*H*) is called 'self-adjoint' or 'Hermitian' if *A** = *A*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *A* is Hermitian and ⟨*Ax*, *x*⟩ ≥ 0 for every *x*, then *A* is called positive, written *A* ≥ 0.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The set of self adjoint operators admits a partial order, in which *A* ≥ *B* if *A* − *B* ≥ 0.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *A* has the form *B***B* for some *B*, then *A* is positive; if *B* is invertible, then *A* is strictly positive.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The spectral theorem gives a precise sense in which self-adjoint operators play the role of real-valued functions: a bounded self-adjoint operator has real spectrum and can be represented, via functional calculus, by multiplication by a real-valued function.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] More generally, a normal operator is analogous to a complex-valued function.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] It decomposes into commuting self-adjoint real and imaginary parts, $A=\operatorname {Re} A+i\operatorname {Im} A={\frac {A+A^{*}}{2}}+i{\frac {A-A^{*}}{2i}}.$ Conversely, if two self-adjoint operators commute, their sum in this form is normal.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] An element *U* of B(*H*) is called unitary if *U* is invertible and its inverse is given by *U**.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This can also be expressed by requiring that *U* be onto and ⟨*Ux*, *Uy*⟩ = ⟨*x*, *y*⟩ for all *x*, *y* ∈ *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The unitary operators form a group under composition, which is the isometry group of *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] An element of B(*H*) is compact if it sends bounded sets to relatively compact sets.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Equivalently, a bounded operator *T* is compact if, for any bounded sequence {*xk*}, the sequence {*Txk*} has a convergent subsequence.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Many integral operators are compact, and define a special class of operators known as Hilbert–Schmidt operators that are important in the study of integral equations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators are bounded operators that are invertible modulo compact operators.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Thus an operator T is Fredholm if there is a bounded operator $T'$ , called a parametrix, such that $TT'-I$ is compact (right-Fredholm) and $T'T-I$ is compact (left-Fredholm).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators are equivalently characterized as bounded operators with a finite dimensional kernel and closed range.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators thus correspond to invertible elements of the Calkin algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators can be intuitively thought of as operators that are invertible modulo finite dimensional effects.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The index of a Fredholm operator *T* is defined by $\operatorname {index} T=\dim \ker T-\dim \operatorname {coker} T\,.$ The index is homotopy invariant, and plays a deep role in differential geometry via the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Unbounded operators arise naturally in Hilbert spaces, especially in the study of differential operators and in the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] An unbounded operator on a Hilbert space *H* is a linear map $T:D(T)\to H$ whose domain *D*(*T*) is a linear subspace of *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Unlike bounded operators, an unbounded operator is usually not defined on all of *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *D*(*T*) is dense in *H*, then *T* is called a densely defined operator.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The domain of an unbounded operator is part of its definition.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In particular, the same formula may define different operators when equipped with different domains.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Operators used in analysis are often required to be closed, meaning that the graph is closed, or closable, meaning that the operator can be extended over a larger domain to an operator whose graph is closed.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] By the closed graph theorem, a closed operator defined on all of a Hilbert space is bounded; hence a genuinely unbounded closed operator must have a proper domain.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *T* is densely defined, its adjoint *T** is defined as follows.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] A vector *y* ∈ *H* belongs to *D*(*T**) if the map $x\mapsto \langle Tx,y\rangle ,\qquad x\in D(T),$ is bounded with respect to the Hilbert-space norm on *D*(*T*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In that case the Riesz representation theorem gives a unique vector *T***y* ∈ *H* such that $\langle Tx,y\rangle =\langle x,T^{*}y\rangle$ for all *x* ∈ *D*(*T*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] A densely defined operator is called symmetric if *T* ⊂ *T**, and self-adjoint if *T* = *T**, including equality of domains.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Self-adjoint unbounded operators play the role of observables in the Hilbert-space formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Equivalently, it is the closure of this differential operator initially defined on compactly supported smooth functions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] These operators are not defined on all of *L*2(**R**): for a general square-integrable function the derivative need not exist, and the product *xf*(*x*) need not be square integrable.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Each of the *H**i* is included as a closed subspace in the direct sum of all of the *H**i*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Moreover, the *H**i* are pairwise orthogonal.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, if there is a system of closed subspaces, *V**i*, *i* ∈ *I*, in a Hilbert space *H*, that are pairwise orthogonal and whose linear span is dense in *H*, then *H* is canonically isomorphic to the direct sum of *Vi*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In this case, *H* is called the internal direct sum of the *Vi*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] A direct sum (internal or external) is also equipped with a family of orthogonal projections *Ei* onto the *i*th direct summand *Hi*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The spectral theorem for compact self-adjoint operators on a Hilbert space *H* states that *H* splits into the orthogonal direct sum of the eigenspaces of an operator, and also gives an explicit decomposition of the operator as a sum of projections onto the eigenspaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The direct sum of Hilbert spaces also appears in quantum mechanics as the Fock space of a system containing a variable number of particles, where each Hilbert space in the direct sum corresponds to an additional degree of freedom for the quantum mechanical system.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In representation theory, the Peter–Weyl theorem guarantees that any unitary representation of a compact group on a Hilbert space splits as the direct sum of finite-dimensional representations.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If $x_{1},y_{1}\in H_{1}$ and $x_{2},y_{2}\in H_{2}$ , then one defines an inner product on the (ordinary) tensor product as follows.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This formula then extends by sesquilinearity to an inner product on $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The Hilbertian tensor product of $H_{1}$ and $H_{2}$ , sometimes denoted by $H_{1}\mathbin {\widehat {\otimes }} H_{2}$ , is the Hilbert space obtained by completing $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$ for the metric associated to this inner product.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This example is typical in the following sense.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This mapping defined on simple tensors extends to a linear identification between $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$ and the space of finite rank operators from $H_{1}^{\ast }$ to $H_{2}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This extends to a linear isometry of the Hilbertian tensor product $H_{1}\mathbin {\widehat {\otimes }} H_{2}$ with the Hilbert space $\operatorname {HS} (H_{1}^{\ast },H_{2})$ of Hilbert–Schmidt operators from $H_{1}^{\ast }$ to $H_{2}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The identification of operators with tensor product spaces generalizes to other tensor norms.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The notion of an orthonormal basis from linear algebra generalizes over to the case of Hilbert spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] *Normalization*: Every element of the family has norm 1: ‖*e**k*‖ = 1 for all *k* ∈ *B*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] *Completeness*: The linear span of the family *e**k*, *k* ∈ *B*, is dense in *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] A system of vectors satisfying the first two conditions basis is called an orthonormal system or an orthonormal set (or an orthonormal sequence if *B* is countable).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Such a system is always linearly independent.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Despite the name, an orthonormal basis is not, in general, a basis in the sense of linear algebra (Hamel basis).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] More precisely, an orthonormal basis is a Hamel basis if and only if the Hilbert space is a finite-dimensional vector space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This is related to the fact that the only vector orthogonal to a dense linear subspace is the zero vector, for if *S* is any orthonormal set and *v* is orthogonal to *S*, then *v* is orthogonal to the closure of the linear span of *S*, which is the whole space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In the infinite-dimensional case, an orthonormal basis will not be a basis in the sense of linear algebra; to distinguish the two, the latter basis is also called a Hamel basis.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] That the span of the basis vectors is dense implies that every vector in the space can be written as the sum of an infinite series, and the orthogonality implies that this decomposition is unique.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This space is the infinite-dimensional generalization of the $\ell _{2}^{n}$ space of finite-dimensional vectors.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] It is usually the first example used to show that in infinite-dimensional spaces, a set that is closed and bounded is not necessarily (sequentially) compact (as is the case in all *finite* dimensional spaces).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Indeed, the set of orthonormal vectors above shows this: It is an infinite sequence of vectors in the unit ball (i.e., the ball of points with norm less than or equal one).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This set is clearly bounded and closed; yet, no subsequence of these vectors converges to anything and consequently the unit ball in $\ell _{2}$ is not compact.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Intuitively, this is because "there is always another coordinate direction" into which the next elements of the sequence can evade.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] One can generalize the space $\ell _{2}$ in many ways.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The summation over *B* is here defined by $\sum _{b\in B}\left|x(b)\right|^{2}=\sup \sum _{n=1}^{N}\left|x(b_{n})\right|^{2}$ the supremum being taken over all finite subsets of *B*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] It follows that, for this sum to be finite, every element of *l*2(*B*) has only countably many nonzero terms.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Here the sum also has only countably many nonzero terms, and is unconditionally convergent by the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Let *f*1, ..., *f**n* be a finite orthonormal system in *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] It follows that *x* − *y* is orthogonal to each *f**k*, hence *x* − *y* is orthogonal to *y*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Let {*f**i*}, *i* ∈ *I*, be an arbitrary orthonormal system in *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Applying the preceding inequality to every finite subset *J* of *I* gives Bessel's inequality: $\sum _{i\in I}{\bigl |}\langle x,f_{i}\rangle {\bigr |}^{2}\leq \|x\|^{2},\quad x\in H$ (according to the definition of the sum of an arbitrary family of non-negative real numbers).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Geometrically, Bessel's inequality implies that the orthogonal projection of *x* onto the linear subspace spanned by the *fi* has norm that does not exceed that of *x*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In two dimensions, this is the assertion that the length of the leg of a right triangle may not exceed the length of the hypotenuse.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Bessel's inequality is a stepping stone to the stronger result called Parseval's identity, which governs the case when Bessel's inequality is actually an equality.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Even if *B* is uncountable, Bessel's inequality guarantees that the expression is well-defined and consists only of countably many nonzero terms.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This sum is called the Fourier expansion of *x*, and the individual coefficients ⟨*x*, *e**k*⟩ are the Fourier coefficients of *x*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, if {*e**k*} is an orthonormal set such that Parseval's identity holds for every *x*, then {*e**k*} is an orthonormal basis.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] As a consequence of Zorn's lemma, *every* Hilbert space admits an orthonormal basis; furthermore, any two orthonormal bases of the same space have the same cardinality, called the Hilbert dimension of the space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] For instance, since *l*2(*B*) has an orthonormal basis indexed by *B*, its Hilbert dimension is the cardinality of *B* (which may be a finite integer, or a countable or uncountable cardinal number).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The Hilbert dimension is not greater than the Hamel dimension (the usual dimension of a vector space).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The cardinal number of *B* is the Hilbert dimension of *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Thus every Hilbert space is isometrically isomorphic to a sequence space *l*2(*B*) for some set *B*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] By definition, a Hilbert space is separable provided it contains a dense countable subset.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Along with Zorn's lemma, this means a Hilbert space is separable if and only if it admits a countable orthonormal basis.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] All infinite-dimensional separable Hilbert spaces are therefore isometrically isomorphic to the square-summable sequence space, $\ell ^{2}.$ Separability was originally part of the definition of Hilbert space (von Neumann 1955), and it is still assumed in physical treatments.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] For instance, Dirac (1974) refers to a separable infinite-dimensional Hilbert space as "*the* Hilbert space" and describes it informally as the limit of an n -dimensional coordinate space as n tends to infinity.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Most spaces used in physics are separable, and since these are all isomorphic to each other, one often refers to any infinite-dimensional separable Hilbert space as "*the* Hilbert space" or just "Hilbert space".
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In the Wightman formulation of relativistic quantum field theory, the state space is likewise assumed to be a separable complex Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] However, it is sometimes argued that non-separable Hilbert spaces are also important in quantum field theory, roughly because the systems in the theory possess an infinite number of degrees of freedom.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] For instance, a bosonic field can be naturally thought of as arising from a tensor-product construction whose factors represent harmonic oscillators at each point of space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] From this perspective, a non-separable full tensor product may appear naturally, although in physical applications one usually works in a distinguished separable subspace or representation on which the observables are defined.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The set *S*⊥ is a closed subspace of *H* (can be proved easily using the linearity and continuity of the inner product) and so forms itself a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *V* is a closed subspace of *H*, then *V*⊥ is called the *orthogonal complement* of *V*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In fact, every *x* ∈ *H* can then be written uniquely as *x* = *v* + *w*, with *v* ∈ *V* and *w* ∈ *V*⊥.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Therefore, *H* is the internal Hilbert direct sum of *V* and *V*⊥.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The linear operator *PV* : *H* → *H* that maps *x* to *v* is called the *orthogonal projection* onto *V*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] There is a natural one-to-one correspondence between the set of all closed subspaces of *H* and the set of all bounded self-adjoint operators *P* such that *P*2 = *P*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This provides the geometrical interpretation of *PV*(*x*): it is the best approximation to *x* by elements of *V*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Projections *PU* and *PV* are called mutually orthogonal if *P**U**P**V* = 0.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This is equivalent to *U* and *V* being orthogonal as subspaces of *H*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The sum of the two projections *P**U* and *P**V* is a projection only if *U* and *V* are orthogonal to each other, and in that case *P**U* + *P**V* = *P**U*+*V*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The composite *P**U**P**V* is generally not a projection; in fact, the composite is a projection if and only if the two projections commute, and in that case *P**U**P**V* = *P**U*∩*V*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Every closed subspace *V* of a Hilbert space is therefore the image of an operator *P* of norm one such that *P*2 = *P*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The orthogonal complement satisfies some more elementary results.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] It is a monotone function in the sense that if *U* ⊂ *V*, then *V*⊥ ⊆ *U*⊥ with equality holding if and only if *V* is contained in the closure of *U*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This result is a special case of the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The closure of a subspace can be completely characterized in terms of the orthogonal complement: if *V* is a subspace of *H*, then the closure of *V* is equal to *V*⊥⊥.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The orthogonal complement is thus a Galois connection on the partial order of subspaces of a Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Spectral theory, for self-adjoint operators in a Hilbert space, is roughly analogous to the study of symmetric matrices over the reals or self-adjoint matrices over the complex numbers.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In the same sense, one can obtain a "diagonalization" of a self-adjoint operator as a suitable sum (actually an integral) of orthogonal projection operators.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The spectrum of an operator *T*, denoted *σ*(*T*), is the set of complex numbers *λ* such that *T* − *λ* lacks a continuous inverse.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *T* is bounded, then the spectrum is always a compact set in the complex plane, and lies inside the disc |*z*| ≤ ‖*T*‖.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] If *T* is self-adjoint, then the spectrum is real.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Moreover, *m* and *M* are both contained within the spectrum.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Unlike with finite matrices, not every element of the spectrum of *T* must be an eigenvalue: the linear operator *T* − *λ* may only lack an inverse because it is not surjective.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Elements of the spectrum of an operator in the general sense are known as *spectral values*.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Since spectral values need not be eigenvalues, the spectral decomposition is often more subtle than in finite dimensions.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] However, the spectral theorem of a self-adjoint operator *T* takes a particularly simple form if, in addition, *T* is assumed to be a compact operator.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This theorem is especially important for integral operators on *L*2 with square-integrable kernels, since these operators are Hilbert–Schmidt and hence compact.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The general spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators involves a kind of operator-valued Riemann–Stieltjes integral, rather than an infinite summation.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The operators *Eλ* are monotone increasing relative to the partial order defined on self-adjoint operators; the eigenvalues correspond precisely to the jump discontinuities.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The integral is understood as a Riemann–Stieltjes integral, convergent with respect to the norm on B(*H*).
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] A somewhat similar spectral decomposition holds for normal operators, although because the spectrum may now contain non-real complex numbers, the operator-valued Stieltjes measure d*Eλ* must instead be replaced by a resolution of the identity.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The resulting continuous functional calculus has applications in particular to pseudodifferential operators.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The spectral theory of *unbounded* self-adjoint operators is only marginally more difficult than for bounded operators.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] fails to be a well-defined continuous operator.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] The self-adjointness of *T* still guarantees that the spectrum is real.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Thus the essential idea of working with unbounded operators is to look instead at the resolvent *Rλ* where *λ* is nonreal.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] This is a *bounded* normal operator, which admits a spectral representation that can then be transferred to a spectral representation of *T* itself.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] Thus the essential idea of working with unbounded operators is to study the resolvent *R**λ* = (*T* − *λ*)−1 on the resolvent set, since it is a bounded operator and can be analyzed by bounded spectral theory.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] There is also a version of the spectral theorem that applies to unbounded normal operators.
[src:operator-algebras/hilbert-space-p02] In *Gravity's Rainbow* (1973), a novel by Thomas Pynchon, one of the characters is called "Sammy Hilbert-Spaess", a pun on "Hilbert Space".
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] In functional analysis, a branch of mathematics, an **operator algebra** is an algebra of continuous linear operators on a topological vector space, with the multiplication given by the composition of mappings.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] The results obtained in the study of operator algebras are often phrased in algebraic terms, while the techniques used are often highly analytic.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] Although the study of operator algebras is usually classified as a branch of functional analysis, it has direct applications to representation theory, differential geometry, quantum statistical mechanics, quantum information, and quantum field theory.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] Operator algebras can be used to study arbitrary sets of operators with little algebraic relation *simultaneously*.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] From this point of view, operator algebras can be regarded as a generalization of spectral theory of a single operator.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] In general, operator algebras are non-commutative rings.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] An operator algebra is typically required to be closed in a specified operator topology inside the whole algebra of continuous linear operators.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] In particular, it is a set of operators with both algebraic and topological closure properties.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] In some disciplines such properties are axiomatized and algebras with certain topological structure become the subject of the research.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] In the case of operators on a Hilbert space, the Hermitian adjoint map on operators gives a natural involution, which provides an additional algebraic structure that can be imposed on the algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] In this context, the best studied examples are self-adjoint operator algebras, meaning that they are closed under taking adjoints.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] These include C*-algebras, von Neumann algebras, and AW*-algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] C*-algebras can be easily characterized abstractly by a condition relating the norm, involution and multiplication.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] Such abstractly defined C*-algebras can be identified to a certain closed subalgebra of the algebra of the continuous linear operators on a suitable Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] A similar result holds for von Neumann algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] Commutative self-adjoint operator algebras can be regarded as the algebra of complex-valued continuous functions on a locally compact space, or that of measurable functions on a standard measurable space.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] Thus, general operator algebras are often regarded as a noncommutative generalizations of these algebras, or the structure of the *base space* on which the functions are defined.
[src:operator-algebras/operator-algebra] This point of view is elaborated as the philosophy of noncommutative geometry, which tries to study various non-classical and/or pathological objects by noncommutative operator algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] Positive-semidefinite operators are denoted as $A\geq 0$ .
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] The operator is said to be **positive-definite**, and written $A>0$ , if $\langle Ax,x\rangle >0$ for all $x\in \mathop {\mathrm {Dom} } (A)\setminus \{0\}$ .
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] Many authors define a **positive operator** A to be a self-adjoint (or at least symmetric) non-negative operator.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] We show below that for a complex Hilbert space the self adjointness follows automatically from non-negativity.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] For a real Hilbert space non-negativity does not imply self adjointness.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] In physics (specifically quantum mechanics), such operators represent quantum states, via the density matrix formalism.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] Take the inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ to be anti-linear on the *first* argument and linear on the second and suppose that A is positive and symmetric, the latter meaning that $\langle Ax,y\rangle =\langle x,Ay\rangle$ .
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] and the fact that $\langle Ax,x\rangle =\langle x,Ax\rangle ,$ for positive operators, show that $\langle Ax,y\rangle =\langle x,Ay\rangle ,$ so A is symmetric.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] In contrast with the complex case, a positive-semidefinite operator on a real Hilbert space $H_{\mathbb {R} }$ may not be symmetric.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] As a counterexample, define $A:\mathbb {R} ^{2}\to \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ to be an operator of rotation by an acute angle $\varphi \in (-\pi /2,\pi /2).$ Then $\langle Ax,x\rangle =\|Ax\|\|x\|\cos \varphi >0,$ but $A^{*}=A^{-1}\neq A,$ so A is not symmetric.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] The fact that A is bounded now follows from the Hellinger–Toeplitz theorem.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] A natural partial ordering of self-adjoint operators arises from the definition of positive operators.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] It can be seen that a similar result as the Monotone convergence theorem holds for monotone increasing, bounded, self-adjoint operators on Hilbert spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] The definition of a quantum system includes a complex separable Hilbert space $H_{\mathbb {C} }$ and a set ${\cal {S}}$ of positive trace-class operators $\rho$ on $H_{\mathbb {C} }$ for which $\mathop {\text{Trace}} \rho =1.$ The set ${\cal {S}}$ is *the set of states*.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] Every $\rho \in {\cal {S}}$ is called a *state* or a *density operator*.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] For $\psi \in H_{\mathbb {C} },$ where $\|\psi \|=1,$ the operator $P_{\psi }$ of projection onto the span of $\psi$ is called a *pure state*.
[src:operator-algebras/positive-operator] (Since each pure state is identifiable with a unit vector $\psi \in H_{\mathbb {C} },$ some sources define pure states to be unit elements from $H_{\mathbb {C} }).$ States that are not pure are called *mixed*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] In mathematics, a **von Neumann algebra** or **W*-algebra** is a *-algebra of bounded operators on a Hilbert space that is closed in the weak operator topology and contains the identity operator.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Von Neumann algebras were originally introduced by John von Neumann, motivated by his study of single operators, group representations, ergodic theory and quantum mechanics.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] His double commutant theorem shows that the analytic definition is equivalent to a purely algebraic definition as an algebra of symmetries.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Von Neumann algebras were first studied by von Neumann (1930) in 1929; he and Francis Murray developed the basic theory, under the original name of **rings of operators**, in a series of papers written in the 1930s and 1940s (F.J.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Introductory accounts of von Neumann algebras are given in the online notes of Jones (2003) and Wassermann (1991) and the books by Dixmier (1981), Schwartz (1967), Blackadar (2005) and Sakai (1971).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The three volume work by Takesaki (1979) gives an encyclopedic account of the theory.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The book by Connes (1994) discusses more advanced topics.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] There are three common ways to define von Neumann algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The first and most common way is to define them as weakly closed *-algebras of bounded operators (on a Hilbert space) containing the identity.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] In this definition the weak (operator) topology can be replaced by many other common topologies including the strong, ultrastrong or ultraweak operator topologies.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The *-algebras of bounded operators that are closed in the norm topology are C*-algebras, so in particular any von Neumann algebra is a C*-algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The second definition is that a von Neumann algebra is a subalgebra of the bounded operators closed under involution (the *-operation) and equal to its double commutant, or equivalently the commutant of some subalgebra closed under *.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The von Neumann double commutant theorem (von Neumann 1930) says that the first two definitions are equivalent.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The first two definitions describe a von Neumann algebra concretely as a set of operators acting on some given Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Sakai (1971) showed that von Neumann algebras can also be defined abstractly as C*-algebras that have a predual; in other words the von Neumann algebra, considered as a Banach space, is the dual of some other Banach space called the predual.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The predual of a von Neumann algebra is in fact unique up to isomorphism.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Some authors use "von Neumann algebra" for the algebras together with a Hilbert space action, and "W*-algebra" for the abstract concept, so a von Neumann algebra is a W*-algebra together with a Hilbert space and a suitable faithful unital action on the Hilbert space.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The concrete and abstract definitions of a von Neumann algebra are similar to the concrete and abstract definitions of a C*-algebra, which can be defined either as norm-closed *-algebras of operators on a Hilbert space, or as Banach *-algebras such that $||aa^{*}||=||a||\ ||a^{*}||$ .
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Some of the terminology in von Neumann algebra theory can be confusing, and the terms often have different meanings outside the subject.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] By forgetting about the topology on a von Neumann algebra, we can consider it a (unital) *-algebra, or just a ring.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Von Neumann algebras are semihereditary: every finitely generated submodule of a projective module is itself projective.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] There have been several attempts to axiomatize the underlying rings of von Neumann algebras, including Baer *-rings and AW*-algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The *-algebra of affiliated operators of a finite von Neumann algebra is a von Neumann regular ring.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The relationship between commutative von Neumann algebras and measure spaces is analogous to that between commutative C*-algebras and locally compact Hausdorff spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Every commutative von Neumann algebra is isomorphic to *L*∞(*X*) for some measure space (*X*, μ) and conversely, for every σ-finite measure space *X*, the *-algebra *L*∞(*X*) is a von Neumann algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Due to this analogy, the theory of von Neumann algebras has been called noncommutative measure theory, while the theory of C*-algebras is sometimes called noncommutative topology (Connes 1994).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Operators *E* in a von Neumann algebra for which *E* = *EE* = *E** are called **projections**; they are exactly the operators which give an orthogonal projection of *H* onto some closed subspace.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A subspace of the Hilbert space *H* is said to **belong to** the von Neumann algebra *M* if it is the image of some projection in *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] This establishes a 1:1 correspondence between projections of *M* and subspaces that belong to *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Informally these are the closed subspaces that can be described using elements of *M*, or that *M* "knows" about.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] It can be shown that the closure of the image of any operator in *M* and the kernel of any operator in *M* belongs to *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Also, the closure of the image under an operator of *M* of any subspace belonging to *M* also belongs to *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] (These results are a consequence of the polar decomposition).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The basic theory of projections was worked out by Murray & von Neumann (1936).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Two subspaces belonging to *M* are called (**Murray–von Neumann**) **equivalent** if there is a partial isometry mapping the first isomorphically onto the other that is an element of the von Neumann algebra (informally, if *M* "knows" that the subspaces are isomorphic).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Another way of stating this is that *E* is equivalent to *F* if *E=uu** and *F=u*u* for some partial isometry *u* in *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The equivalence relation ~ thus defined is additive in the following sense: Suppose *E*1 ~ *F*1 and *E*2 ~ *F*2.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Additivity would *not* generally hold if one were to require unitary equivalence in the definition of ~, i.e. if we say *E* is equivalent to *F* if *u*Eu* = *F* for some unitary *u*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The Schröder–Bernstein theorems for operator algebras gives a sufficient condition for Murray-von Neumann equivalence.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The subspaces belonging to *M* are partially ordered by inclusion, and this induces a partial order ≤ of projections.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] There is also a natural partial order on the set of *equivalence classes* of projections, induced by the partial order ≤ of projections.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] If *M* is a factor, ≤ is a total order on equivalence classes of projections, described in the section on traces below.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A projection (or subspace belonging to *M*) *E* is said to be a **finite projection** if there is no projection *F* < *E* (meaning *F* ≤ *E* and *F* ≠ *E*) that is equivalent to *E*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] However it is possible for infinite dimensional subspaces to be finite.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Orthogonal projections are noncommutative analogues of indicator functions in *L*∞(**R**).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] *L*∞(**R**) is the ||·||∞-closure of the subspace generated by the indicator functions.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Similarly, a von Neumann algebra is generated by its projections; this is a consequence of the spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The projections of a finite factor form a continuous geometry.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A von Neumann algebra *N* whose center consists only of multiples of the identity operator is called a **factor**.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] As von Neumann (1949) showed, every von Neumann algebra on a separable Hilbert space is isomorphic to a direct integral of factors.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] This decomposition is essentially unique.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Thus, the problem of classifying isomorphism classes of von Neumann algebras on separable Hilbert spaces can be reduced to that of classifying isomorphism classes of factors.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Murray & von Neumann (1936) showed that every factor has one of 3 types as described below.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The type classification can be extended to von Neumann algebras that are not factors, and a von Neumann algebra is of type X if it can be decomposed as a direct integral of type X factors; for example, every commutative von Neumann algebra has type I1.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Every von Neumann algebra can be written uniquely as a sum of von Neumann algebras of types I, II, and III.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A factor is said to be of **type I** if there is a minimal projection *E ≠ 0*, i.e. a projection *E* such that there is no other projection *F* with 0 < *F* < *E*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Any factor of type I is isomorphic to the von Neumann algebra of *all* bounded operators on some Hilbert space; since there is one Hilbert space for every cardinal number, isomorphism classes of factors of type I correspond exactly to the cardinal numbers.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Since many authors consider von Neumann algebras only on separable Hilbert spaces, it is customary to call the bounded operators on a Hilbert space of finite dimension *n* a factor of type I*n*, and the bounded operators on a separable infinite-dimensional Hilbert space, a factor of type I∞.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A factor is said to be of **type II** if there are no minimal projections but there are non-zero finite projections.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] This implies that every projection *E* can be "halved" in the sense that there are two projections *F* and *G* that are Murray–von Neumann equivalent and satisfy *E* = *F* + *G*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] If the identity operator in a type II factor is finite, the factor is said to be of type II1; otherwise, it is said to be of type II∞.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The best understood factors of type II are the hyperfinite type II1 factor and the hyperfinite type II∞ factor, found by Murray & von Neumann (1936).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] These are the unique hyperfinite factors of types II1 and II∞; there are an uncountable number of other factors of these types that are the subject of intensive study.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Murray & von Neumann (1937) proved the fundamental result that a factor of type II1 has a unique finite tracial state, and the set of traces of projections is [0,1].
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A factor of type II∞ has a semifinite trace, unique up to rescaling, and the set of traces of projections is [0,∞].
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The set of real numbers λ such that there is an automorphism rescaling the trace by a factor of λ is called the **fundamental group** of the type II∞ factor.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The tensor product of a factor of type II1 and an infinite type I factor has type II∞, and conversely any factor of type II∞ can be constructed like this.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The **fundamental group** of a type II1 factor is defined to be the fundamental group of its tensor product with the infinite (separable) factor of type I.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Subsequently, Sorin Popa showed that the fundamental group can be trivial for certain groups, including the semidirect product of **Z**2 by SL(2,**Z**).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] An example of a type II1 factor is the group von Neumann algebra of a countable infinite discrete group such that every non-trivial conjugacy class is infinite.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] McDuff (1969) found an uncountable family of such groups with non-isomorphic group von Neumann algebras, thus showing the existence of uncountably many different separable type II1 factors.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Lastly, **type III** factors are factors that do not contain any nonzero finite projections at all.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] In their first paper Murray & von Neumann (1936) were unable to decide whether or not they existed; the first examples were later found by von Neumann (1940).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Since the identity operator is always infinite in those factors, they were sometimes called type III∞ in the past, but recently that notation has been superseded by the notation IIIλ, where λ is a real number in the interval [0,1].
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] More precisely, if the Connes spectrum (of its modular group) is 1 then the factor is of type III0, if the Connes spectrum is all integral powers of λ for 0 < λ < 1, then the type is IIIλ, and if the Connes spectrum is all positive reals then the type is III1.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] (The Connes spectrum is a closed subgroup of the positive reals, so these are the only possibilities.) The only trace on type III factors takes value ∞ on all non-zero positive elements, and any two non-zero projections are equivalent.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] At one time type III factors were considered to be intractable objects, but Tomita–Takesaki theory has led to a good structure theory.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] In particular, any type III factor can be written in a canonical way as the crossed product of a type II∞ factor and the real numbers.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Any von Neumann algebra *M* has a **predual** *M*∗, which is the Banach space of all ultraweakly continuous linear functionals on *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] As the name suggests, *M* is (as a Banach space) the dual of its predual.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The predual is unique in the sense that any other Banach space whose dual is *M* is canonically isomorphic to *M*∗.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Sakai (1971) showed that the existence of a predual characterizes von Neumann algebras among C* algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The definition of the predual given above seems to depend on the choice of Hilbert space that *M* acts on, as this determines the ultraweak topology.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] However the predual can also be defined without using the Hilbert space that *M* acts on, by defining it to be the space generated by all positive **normal** linear functionals on *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The predual *M*∗ is a closed subspace of the dual *M** (which consists of all norm-continuous linear functionals on *M*) but is generally smaller.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The proof that *M*∗ is (usually) not the same as *M** is nonconstructive and uses the axiom of choice in an essential way; it is very hard to exhibit explicit elements of *M** that are not in *M*∗.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] For example, exotic positive linear forms on the von Neumann algebra *l*∞(*Z*) are given by free ultrafilters; they correspond to exotic *-homomorphisms into *C* and describe the Stone–Čech compactification of *Z*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The predual of the von Neumann algebra *B*(*H*) of bounded operators on a Hilbert space *H* is the Banach space of all trace class operators with the trace norm ||*A*||= Tr(|*A*|).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The Banach space of trace class operators is itself the dual of the C*-algebra of compact operators (which is not a von Neumann algebra).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The predual of the group von Neumann algebra *VN*(*G*) associated to the left regular representation of a locally compact group *G* is the Fourier algebra *A*(*G*).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Weights and their special cases states and traces are discussed in detail in (Takesaki 1979).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Any factor has a trace such that the trace of a non-zero projection is non-zero and the trace of a projection is infinite if and only if the projection is infinite.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] For factors that are separable or finite, two projections are equivalent if and only if they have the same trace.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] If a von Neumann algebra acts on a Hilbert space containing a norm 1 vector *v*, then the functional *a* → (*av*,*v*) is a normal state.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] This construction can be reversed to give an action on a Hilbert space from a normal state: this is the GNS construction for normal states.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Given an abstract separable factor, one can ask for a classification of its modules, meaning the separable Hilbert spaces that it acts on.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The answer is given as follows: every such module *H* can be given an *M*-dimension dim*M*(*H*) (not its dimension as a complex vector space) such that modules are isomorphic if and only if they have the same *M*-dimension.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The *M*-dimension is additive, and a module is isomorphic to a subspace of another module if and only if it has smaller or equal *M*-dimension.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A module is called **standard** if it has a cyclic separating vector.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Each factor has a standard representation, which is unique up to isomorphism.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The standard representation has an antilinear involution *J* such that *JMJ* = *M′*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] For finite factors the standard module is given by the GNS construction applied to the unique normal tracial state and the *M*-dimension is normalized so that the standard module has *M*-dimension 1, while for infinite factors the standard module is the module with *M*-dimension equal to ∞.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] There is no generally accepted term for the class of algebras above; Connes has suggested that **amenable** should be the standard term.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The amenable factors have been classified: there is a unique one of each of the types I*n*, I∞, II1, II∞, IIIλ, for 0 < λ ≤ 1, and the ones of type III0 correspond to certain ergodic flows.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] All amenable factors can be constructed using the **group-measure space construction** of Murray and von Neumann for a single ergodic transformation.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] In fact they are precisely the factors arising as crossed products by free ergodic actions of *Z* or *Z/nZ* on abelian von Neumann algebras *L*∞(*X*).
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Type I factors occur when the measure space *X* is atomic and the action transitive.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] When *X* is diffuse or non-atomic, it is equivalent to [0,1] as a measure space.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Type II factors occur when *X* admits an equivalent finite (II1) or infinite (II∞) measure, invariant under an action of *Z*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Type III factors occur in the remaining cases where there is no invariant measure, but only an invariant measure class: these factors are called **Krieger factors**.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The Hilbert space tensor product of two Hilbert spaces is the completion of their algebraic tensor product.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] One can define a tensor product of von Neumann algebras (a completion of the algebraic tensor product of the algebras considered as rings), which is again a von Neumann algebra, and act on the tensor product of the corresponding Hilbert spaces.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The tensor product of two finite algebras is finite, and the tensor product of an infinite algebra and a non-zero algebra is infinite.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The type of the tensor product of two von Neumann algebras (I, II, or III) is the maximum of their types.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] where *M′* denotes the commutant of *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The tensor product of an infinite number of von Neumann algebras, if done naively, is usually a ridiculously large non-separable algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Instead von Neumann (1938) showed that one should choose a state on each of the von Neumann algebras, use this to define a state on the algebraic tensor product, which can be used to produce a Hilbert space and a (reasonably small) von Neumann algebra.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Araki & Woods (1968) studied the case where all the factors are finite matrix algebras; these factors are called **Araki–Woods** factors or **ITPFI factors** (ITPFI stands for "infinite tensor product of finite type I factors").
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The type of the infinite tensor product can vary dramatically as the states are changed; for example, the infinite tensor product of an infinite number of type I2 factors can have any type depending on the choice of states.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] All hyperfinite von Neumann algebras not of type III0 are isomorphic to Araki–Woods factors, but there are uncountably many of type III0 that are not.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] A **bimodule** (or correspondence) is a Hilbert space *H* with module actions of two commuting von Neumann algebras.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Bimodules have a much richer structure than that of modules.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Any bimodule over two factors always gives a subfactor since one of the factors is always contained in the commutant of the other.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] There is also a subtle relative tensor product operation due to Connes on bimodules.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The theory of subfactors, initiated by Vaughan Jones, reconciles these two seemingly different points of view.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Bimodules are also important for the von Neumann group algebra *M* of a discrete group Γ.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Indeed, if *V* is any unitary representation of Γ, then, regarding Γ as the diagonal subgroup of Γ × Γ, the corresponding induced representation on *l*2 (Γ, *V*) is naturally a bimodule for two commuting copies of *M*.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Important representation theoretic properties of Γ can be formulated entirely in terms of bimodules and therefore make sense for the von Neumann algebra itself.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] For example, Connes and Jones gave a definition of an analogue of Kazhdan's property (T) for von Neumann algebras in this way.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Von Neumann algebras of type I are always amenable, but for the other types there are an uncountable number of different non-amenable factors, which seem very hard to classify, or even distinguish from each other.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Nevertheless, Voiculescu has shown that the class of non-amenable factors coming from the group-measure space construction is **disjoint** from the class coming from group von Neumann algebras of free groups.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Later Narutaka Ozawa proved that group von Neumann algebras of hyperbolic groups yield prime type II1 factors, i.e. ones that cannot be factored as tensor products of type II1 factors, a result first proved by Leeming Ge for free group factors using Voiculescu's free entropy.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Popa's work on fundamental groups of non-amenable factors represents another significant advance.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] The theory of factors "beyond the hyperfinite" is rapidly expanding at present, with many new and surprising results; it has close links with rigidity phenomena in geometric group theory and ergodic theory.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] Von Neumann algebras have found applications in diverse areas of mathematics like knot theory, statistical mechanics, quantum field theory, local quantum physics, free probability, noncommutative geometry, representation theory, differential geometry, and dynamical systems.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] For instance, C*-algebra provides an alternative axiomatization to probability theory.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] In this case the method goes by the name of Gelfand–Naimark–Segal construction.
[src:operator-algebras/von-neumann-algebra] This is analogous to the two approaches to measure and integration, where one has the choice to construct measures of sets first and define integrals later, or construct integrals first and define set measures as integrals of characteristic functions.
